<font color="#FF0000">NOTES ON &quot;GOOK&quot; AND &quot;PTSD&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Mon Mar 17  2:00:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
1. Chris,<br>
Felt a need to rebut just one point you made a few posts back, namely that the Army indoctrinated everybody to dehumanize the enemy by labeling them gooks.  Outside of bayonet training, which probably dehumanizes the trainee more than anything; I was never so indoctrinated.  Went through Infantry Officers' Basic at Ft. Benning from 11/26/67 to 2/13/68.  Heard the terms &quot;VC&quot; and &quot;Charlie&quot; quite regularly, but never heard the term &quot;gook&quot; till I got to Vietnam, and then very rarely from other officers.  The term had a large racist component; as it was more than occasionally used to refer to any Vietnmamese, not just the enemy.  It also drew on the frustration of not knowing whether the Mama-san cleaning your hooch was just cleaning or also stepping off distances for a VC mortar squad, or the  not knowing whether the South Vietnamese troops on your joint operation would perform well (and often they did) or leave your guys holding the bag (and that happened often also).  This doesn't excuse the term, but shows the environment it came out of.<br><br>
2. JJ,<br>
The WWII Vet father of a Vietnam Vet I know recently went into the hospital for a magetic resonnance image scanning.  In over 50 years, he never previously showed PTSD symptoms. Being encased with metal with the machine clanking away, he suddenly found himself back in the midst of a 1944 tank battle where his tank had taken a hit or two.  He freaked out. and the doctors and nurses didn't have a clue, except that their patient was evidently going nuts.  Fortunately his daughter-in-law was present and able to figure out what was going on.<br>
Meanwhile Gov. Ridge here in Pa zeroed out the funding for the program that was training medical personnel how to recognize PTSD because it supposedly wasn't needed any more.  And oh yes, he ran as a Vietnam Vet.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot; 7-68/7/69) </code><p>


